1
00:00:00,050 --> 00:00:07,354
Agent Quarantine is a local command firewall for AI coding
agents. It is not a sandbox; it is a PATH shim safety
layer.

2
00:00:07,454 --> 00:00:16,758
The boundary is explicit. Common tools are intercepted by
shims, dangerous commands are blocked, risky commands ask
for approval, and every decision is logged.

3
00:00:16,858 --> 00:00:25,600
Demo one. A remote script downloaded with curl and
immediately piped into sh is blocked by default, because
it gives the remote server code execution.

4
00:00:25,700 --> 00:00:35,058
Demo two. Searching dot env for an API key with grep is
blocked as credential file read. Read-only tools are not
safe when they are pointed at secret files.

5
00:00:35,158 --> 00:00:45,250
Preflight scans the repository before the agent starts. In
the sample repo, it finds an npm lifecycle script and an
instruction that tells the agent to ignore safety.

6
00:00:45,350 --> 00:00:52,541
The report command turns a JSONL session log into
Markdown, preserving which command was blocked and the
reason for that decision.

7
00:00:52,641 --> 00:01:01,222
Agent Quarantine is honest about its boundary. It is not a
virtual machine or kernel sandbox, and absolute path
binaries can bypass PATH shims.

8
00:01:01,322 --> 00:01:10,944
Before handing an unfamiliar repo to an AI agent, Agent
Quarantine gives you a practical first layer that stops
common dangerous commands and creates a readable audit
trail.
